people.name: Marton
people.personal_description: I am an automotive engineer (MSc) with origins in Hungary and almost 5 years of work experience in quality management (Porsche Motorsport). Having a strong affinity for design, a digital mindset and passion for new technologies and usability, I shifted my career to interaction design. As a reliable team player, characterized by pragmatic and precise way of working, empathy and customer orientation, I aim to contribute to shaping user experiences of future mobility.
people.project01_description:
Photography is a passion of mine, a hobby I have had for a long time. The two-dimensional frame is an area, a tool for me to express my visual cognition and view of our world. Minimalistic compositions, special play of light and shadow, details of our surroundings shown in unusual, exciting, visually pleasing yet ambiguous ways – the viewers should have second thoughts about what they are actually seeing.

A larger collection can be seen on my website – see contact details.
people.project02_contributors: Communication design support by Julia Kassin
people.project02_description:
This interactive poster deals with the topic of concentration and distractions in a permanently buzzing and overloaded environment. In our dynamic world we have to focus on every information precisely if we want to understand it. This poster forces the viewer to focus on one information source long enough to be able to read the messages, shown slowly character by character. While doing so, coloured characters start to pulse at other locations to distract the spectator.

With the help of eye-tracking, the messages are displayed in the focus of the viewer’s gaze and every eye movement in different directions can reset the message display – so that the viewer needs to start over focusing again.

The project was created for the exhibition “The Next Poster” at the Designforum Steiermark, shown between Sept.-Dec. 2022.
people.project03_contributors: Nikolaos Goutzeris, Laura Varhegyi, Victoria Reichinger
people.project03_description:
Illumimo is a game using Leap Motion hand tracking to control a scarabeus flying through the ancient Egyptian desert, collecting pieces of the stolen light to bring it back to the temple of Ra. Spiders and snakes chase and attack the flying protagonist on its way, trying to prevent the liberation of the Sungod.

The project was done in Unity. In the development group with 3 fellow students, my part was the programming of the interaction with the hand tracking sensor as well as the flight dynamics and the player-enemy interactions.

people.name: Alicia
people.personal_description:
Hey there, I'm Alicia!

I'm a designer who is always looking for ways to improve and challenge myself. I see myself as a bridge between the creative and technical aspects of design, and I'm really into web development and interactive interfaces.

I'm passionate about design and can't wait to see where my curiosity and drive take me in the future. I believe that by constantly learning and getting better, I can be a valuable addition to any team and make a big impact in the world of design.
people.project01_description:
Our society today bases its communications on digital media. In other words, we connect with people through a screen, a fact that has become more noticeable since the onset of the pandemic.

Even so, human connection is still very important and necessary, and this poster aims to demonstrate this through an interaction between two users.

The poster features two interactive touchpoints that will allow users to connect with the poster. However, the final message will not be visible until both users interacting with each touchpoint connect with each other to close a circuit and show the moral of the work.

This poster was shown in “The Next Poster” exhibition in Graz, Austria.
people.project02_description:
This study proposes the development of an interactive space for children aged 6 to 8 to learn about themselves through Multiple Intelligences.

The goal is to use Information and Communication Technologies (ICT) and apply Universal Design Principles to create a playful, educational interface that promotes the recognition and application of Multiple Intelligences. That way different forms of intelligence beyond linguistic and logical-mathematical knowledge are highlighted.

To this end, the conceptualisation of a dynamic environment based on the idea of fun and learning is proposed. This will be possible thanks to the ideation and design of an interactive installation that will help the public to understand what Multiple Intelligences are and, through a questionnaire, find out which of them they have developed the most.

This project was presented as the master's Thesis in the MA Visual Arts and Media (Valencia, Spain).
people.project03_description:
Valencia 4CHANGE aims to activate a process of change through the involvement of the city's inhabitants by means of daily actions and fun through everyday actions and challenges that add up to the achievement of the SDGs, achieving, at the same time, enjoyment, awareness and commitment.

Aimed mainly at citizens of Valencia between 15 and 40 years old, it uses interactive systems and gamification as a means of interaction to create a more engaging and fun experience.

Valencia 4CHANGE raises awareness through 4 main areas: a) Art and Culture; b) Environment; c) Equality; d) Health and Safety; e) Culture; c) Equality; d) Health and well-being.

This project was presented as the bachelor's Thesis in the BA Design and Creative Technologies (Valencia, Spain) and won the 2nd Price in the 7th Edition of the University Entrepreneur Competition STARTUPV 2k20 (December 2020).

people.project01_description: Posters and adverts consume a lot of energy while they are lit until late at night, but most of the time, they are by themselves. No one there to look at them, engage with them – only burning electricity and causing light pollution. And adding insult to injury, nobody was asked if they wanted exposure to said poster in the first place. With this poster, its contents are only revealed when someone is present and physically interacts with a button press. It not only saves energy; it also gives back control to the viewer: with an opt-in-approach if they choose to view the poster by their own free will – preventing unsolicited exposure – ultimately making it a “wanted” poster.

people.project02_description: We developed a concept and prototype for a navigation app for the KIÖR (Kunst im öffentlichen Raum Steiermark) Institute in Styria. The goal of the app is to raise awareness of and sensitize people to the art and other notable features in these public spaces. It primarily provides information about existing public art and enables navigation between these special locations. The app was designed to have a creative and innovative approach that can be easily edited by the KIOER institute. It was also important to involve the users, who can contribute their own findings and locations through the app for others to discover.
people.project03_description: DECAY is a horror-exploration game concept developed with Unity, set in an abandoned bunker facility that appears to have been the site of questionable experiments. Players can roam the dilapidated hallways using their phone as a controller with OSC and uncover the secrets of this place, including the stories of what happened there. The environment is filled with mini stories that reveal gruesome tales waiting to be discovered. But be warned, there may still be some former inhabitants lurking in the shadows...

people.name: Olena
people.personal_description: Hi! I am happy you are reading this 😊 My name is Olena but call me Lena, please. As a User Experience Designer, I am passionate about creating user oriented, intuitive, functional and aesthetically pleasing designs. I am excited to be a part of creating products that people love to use. I believe that good design should be invisible. I hope our professional roads will cross in the future.
people.project01_description: The task was to design a creative marketing campaign for ASUS Germany. The main goal was to show off two of the newest company laptops - ASUS OLED and ASUS Zenbook Duo - with maximum creativity and differentiation. One campaign for two products, with the most efficient way possible to highlight the product values. The whole idea was to play a concert online. We needed to find local groups and make it a huge event. We had to create a platform that would be linked to the main ASUS website. Users had three screens at their disposal. The first screen showed a concert by the group and was a normal screen. The second screen was to be a colour dance and was called OLED mode to show how much different an ordinary screen differs from a screen with OLED technology. The third screen was supposed to show the scene from different perspectives and was meant to show what was happening outside the main screen. We did it to show the user that he will always see more with the ASUS ZenBook Duo.
people.project02_contributors: Christoph Bus, Lucia Perez Diego, Alicia Martinez Lopez, Selina May
people.project02_description: Together with the university group, we were creating a project for the Klanglicht festival in Graz. The main topic of the exhibition was “Growth”. Each student's group based on their creative approach was showing this topic by producing a light installation with music. In our group, we choose to show the increasing amount of internet traffic. This growth has been significant in recent years, driven by the increasing number of people and devices accessing the internet, as well as the growing amount of data being transmitted for various purposes The sound is showing us the history of the internet by playing sounds from the very earliest times to the latest. Each light colour represents different sound groups for example notification, AI voice, etc. One can differentiate easily how internet traffic has changed and how much it was growing with time.
people.project03_contributors: Colin Kavanagh, Andrea Paricio, Monika Uzelac
people.project03_description: “Flunky ball” it's a first-player perspective game developed in Unity for two or more people. It simulates a real flunky ball game. To start playing you will need your friend, phone, computer, and a can or two of beer. The point of the game is to drink your beer faster than your opponent. To start drinking first you must knock down a bottle of water that stands between you and another player. After you succeed, drink as much as possible, the task of your opponent is to pick up the bottle and return to its first place. Once they finish the task you should stop drinking immediately. You can complete the running action by moving your phone, to win the game you need to shake it as hard as possible and drink beer quickly. Now you can play Flunky ball with your friends from all over the world.
